[A 28 Jun 2022 report stated that the US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention announced on Tuesday (28 Jun 2022) the activation of its Emergency Operations Center (EOC) to respond to the US monkeypox outbreak. The activation of the EOC "allows the agency to further increase operational support for the response to meet the outbreak's evolving challenges," the agency said in a news release. (https://edition.cnn.com/2022/06/28/health/cdc-eoc-monkeypox/index.html)

A ProMED reader, John Klopfer (<johnklopfer@gmail.com>) asks, "Would ProMED be able to post an RFI on efforts to expand wastewater testing for monkeypox (how many sites are operational, and what plans are there to expand the network on what timeframe)? There are some concerning reports that clinics are refusing to test individuals who don't meet the narrow population criteria (e.g. MSM or recent travel). Wastewater might be a better way to get on top of how many cases there are in circulation, and where."

Promed thanks John Klopfer for the question and would welcome a response from the San Francisco or other officials who are operating the waste water testing effort. - Mod.TY]

